    - m_Type: 0
      Title:
        m_Untranslated: Fixed exposure
      Text:
        m_Untranslated: 'Exposure is easiest to explain when it is not set up properly.
          Let''s override the exposure globally.

          

          1) Right
          click in the <i>Hierarchy</i> window, <b>Volume</b> > <b>Global Volume</b>

          

          2)
          In the <i>Inspector</i>, click the <b>New</b> button

          

          3)
          Set the Priority to 10. This way we will ignore all the existing exposure
          settings in the scene set by other volumes which use a lower priority.

          

          4)
          Add Override <b>Exposure</b>

          

          5) Set Mode to Fixed

          

          6)
          Set the Fixed Exposure value to 0. Notice everything is suddenly very bright.
          Look around in the scene: other rooms are almost solidwhite

          

          7)
          Using the slider, increase the Exposure to 3. The 3rd room should look
          more correct now, but the other ones are still overexposed.

          

          This
          is the downside of the fixed exposure, it works well in an evenly lit environment
          but would require additional work to set up the other rooms.

'
